    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>St James' Sqre Satdy.-- 2 o'clock</p>
      <p>My Dearest. Read the enclosed from Will, &amp; if you approve my answer, please send it forthwith.-- Conceive my annoyance &amp; vexation at finding pictures, furniture, all uncovered, curtains and cornices put up, all in short arranged here as for a</p>
      <p>London campaign. And this after the trouble Hester &amp; I took to direct everything that was to be done.-- The housemaid chose to do it all on her own responsibility on hearing first that the baby was ill, saying she felt then quite sure we should all come to be established in Town again. I cannot say how vexed I am at our having to pay the upholsterer's time in consequence</p>
      <p>of this woman's very well intended but extremely officious piece of incongruous reasoning.</p>
      <p>I also hear the disagreeable intelligence that the house is swarming [double underlined] with bugs;-- literally swarming. Something must be done.--</p>
      <p>My journey was most prosperous, the carriage apparently very light, &amp; wonderfully easy.--</p>
      <p>The Avis</p>
      <p>I forgot to direct Green about walking up the hills.-- Tell</p>
      <p>Hester with my love, that if I go on at my present rate, I shall soon be not only thin enough, but too thin. My habit has just been tried on, &amp; is actually hanging about me, so that I am obliged to send for the tailor to take it in by two or three inches, &amp; this only since Monday last.-- Stays, gown, everything is getting looser &amp; looser each day.</p>
    </div></body>
